With this additive model, I ask whether diet and time each have an effect on chick mass, assuming that the diet effect is the same at both time points.

## Interaction in Factorial ANOVA

If the effect of diet changes with time, the additive model is too simple. We then include an interaction term:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
summary(aov(weight ~ Diet * Time, data = chicks_two_way))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
Diet         3  39595   13198   6.839 0.000343 ***
Time         1 734353  734353 380.521  < 2e-16 ***
Diet:Time    3  30504   10168   5.269 0.002187 ** 
Residuals   87 167898    1930                     
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
```


:::
:::


The interaction addresses the question whether diet-related differences are the same at Time 0 and Time 21. Stated differently, does the effect of diet change depending on when we sample the chicks? In this subset, yes, it depends. The interaction term is significant, so the effect of diet depends on time. [Chapter 15](15-interaction-effects.qmd) develops the interpretation of interactions in much more detail.

